<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="templates">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd-planning</domain>
    <summary>Canonical templates for every SDD artifact: Constitution, Spec, Design, Implementation Plan, Task, Roadmap, Backlog Item, Confidence Check, Pattern Record, and Mistake Record.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>sdd</tag>
      <tag>template</tag>
      <tag>spec</tag>
      <tag>design</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>SDD Document Templates</title>

    <summary>A collection of canonical templates for every SDD artifact: Constitution, Spec, Design, Implementation Plan, Task, Roadmap, Backlog Item, Confidence Check, Pattern Record, and Mistake Record. Use these as output schemas — provide a template in the system prompt, instruct the agent to fill each section, and enforce that no non-standard sections are added.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Without fixed schemas, agents invent non-standard sections, omit required fields, and produce inconsistent output across sessions. Templates constrain output structure and ensure executor agents can parse task files predictably. The Confidence Check template enforces explicit quality gates at phase transitions; the Pattern/Mistake Record templates enable agent self-logging and cross-session learning.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting any SDD artifact from scratch — always start from the relevant template.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new project: the Constitution template captures tech stack and standards before feature work begins.</item>
        <item>When a subagent must produce a spec, design, task, or implementation plan with consistent structure.</item>
        <item>Generating backlog items, roadmap entries, or confidence-check reports during planning sessions.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When an SDD artifact already exists and only needs incremental updates — edit in place.</item>
        <item>For one-off notes or research spikes that do not feed into task execution.</item>
        <item>Generating freeform documentation not part of the SDD lifecycle.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="artifact-templates-core-five">
      <p>Templates for Constitution, Spec, Design, Task, and Implementation Plan — the five core SDD artifacts an agent must produce with consistent structure.</p>

      <section name="constitution-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>Use the Constitution template for every new project before any feature work begins. It is the only artifact that does not change per-feature.</statement>
          <rationale>Constitution captures tech stack, standards, and quality gates in one place. Agents reference it in every spec and task to avoid reinventing decisions already made.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/constitution.md">Fillable Constitution skeleton with vision, tech stack table, architecture patterns, code standards, git workflow, project structure, quality gates, principles.</reference>
      </section>

      <section name="specification-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>Provide the spec template as part of the system prompt when generating a spec. Instruct the agent to fill each section and output only the filled template — do not add sections not in the template.</statement>
          <rationale>Constrains output structure; prevents agents from inventing non-standard sections like "Technical Notes" or "Architecture" that belong in design.md.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Spec template key fields: Version, Status (Draft/Review/Approved), Problem Statement (Who/Problem/Impact/Solution/Success Metric), User Personas, User Stories (As a / I want / So that / Priority), FR table (ID, Requirement, Traces To, Priority), NFR table (ID, Category, Requirement, Target), AC in Given-When-Then, Out of Scope table, Assumptions, Dependencies, Related Features.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="implementation-plan-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>The Implementation Plan template wave/checkpoint structure must be preserved intact — the executor agent relies on it to process tasks in dependency order without re-reading the entire plan.</statement>
          <rationale>If wave boundaries are removed or merged, the executor cannot determine which tasks are safe to run in parallel and which must wait.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/implementation-plan.md">Fillable Implementation Plan skeleton with overview, task summary table (Task/Name/Complexity/Est.Tokens/Depends On/Enables), dependency graph, execution waves with checkpoints, task detail blocks, quality gates, FR/AD coverage matrix, risks.</reference>
        <p>Token estimation guide for common components:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Django model (simple): 5-10k tokens</item>
          <item>Django model (complex): 15-25k tokens</item>
          <item>Service class: 20-40k tokens</item>
          <item>ViewSet: 15-30k tokens</item>
          <item>Serializer: 5-15k tokens</item>
          <item>Test file: 20-40k tokens</item>
          <item>React component (simple): 5-10k tokens</item>
          <item>React component (complex): 15-30k tokens</item>
          <item>API endpoint: 10-20k tokens</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>When uncertain about a token estimate, estimate higher and split the task.</statement>
          <rationale>Underestimates cause mid-execution context overflow; the executor produces incomplete output and marks the task done without detecting failure.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="task-file-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>Every TASK_*.md file must include Metadata (Complexity, Est. Tokens, Priority), SDD References (spec, design, plan links), Task Dependency Tree, Objective, Dependencies (with reasons), Acceptance Criteria, Technical Approach (steps), Files to change, and token budget.</statement>
          <rationale>The executor agent stops at BLOCKED status. Missing fields mean the executor cannot proceed; it will either produce wrong output or halt without logging the reason.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Leaving {placeholder} text in non-obvious fields after template fill (e.g., "Project: {project-name}").</description>
          <reason>Agents filling templates miss placeholder fields in metadata; run grep for '{' in generated docs before committing.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="planning-templates">
      <p>Templates for Roadmap, Backlog Item, Grooming Session, Confidence Check, Pattern Record, and Mistake Record — the artifacts that support planning, triage, and cross-session learning.</p>

      <section name="roadmap-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>Roadmap items in the "Now" bucket must have a target milestone and a status (On Track / At Risk / Delayed). "Later" items carry no target — only thematic groupings.</statement>
          <rationale>Concrete targets in "Now" create accountability; absent targets in "Later" prevent false precision for work that will change as earlier work lands.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/roadmap.md">Roadmap skeleton: Vision, Now (current quarter with milestone + feature status), Next (next quarter with confidence level), Later (themes only), Not Planned list, Dependencies table, Change Log.</reference>
      </section>

      <section name="backlog-item-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>Every backlog item must include a RICE score section before it is promoted from ideas/ to validated/. Agent-generated RICE numbers must be flagged as "estimate-needed" when Reach or Impact inputs are not grounded in real data.</statement>
          <rationale>RICE scores generated without real data are illustrative only. Flagging them prevents false ranking precision that leads to executing low-value work first.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/backlog-item.md">Backlog item skeleton with ID, Status lifecycle, Priority P0-P3, Summary, Problem, Proposed Solution, User Stories, RICE table, MoSCoW checkboxes, Dependencies, Risks, Next Steps.</reference>
      </section>

      <section name="confidence-check-template">
        <rule>
          <statement>Run the Confidence Check template at four explicit gates: Pre-Spec, Pre-Design, Pre-Task, Pre-Implementation. Skip none. The "Open Questions" section blocks Approved status — unresolved questions are blockers, not optional notes.</statement>
          <rationale>Advancing with unresolved questions causes rework in later phases. The Confidence Check makes ambiguities visible before the cost of fixing them rises.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/confidence-check.md">Confidence Check skeleton: Phase, Score table (Check/Weight/Status/Evidence), Verdict (Proceed/Clarify/Stop), Questions to Answer First, Recommended Actions.</reference>
      </section>

      <section name="pattern-and-mistake-records">
        <rule>
          <statement>After each task execution, the executor agent appends a Pattern Record or Mistake Record to .aidocs/memory/. These must be indexed so future agents can find and apply prior learnings without repeating mistakes.</statement>
          <rationale>Agents that cannot find prior patterns repeat mistakes. The structured JSON format enables programmatic search and aggregation across sessions.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <reference path="templates/pattern-record.json">JSON schema: id (PAT-NNN), timestamp, project, task_type, pattern_name, description, context (when to use), code_example, success_count, tags.</reference>
        <reference path="templates/mistake-record.json">JSON schema: id (ERR-NNN), timestamp, project, task_type, error_type, description, root_cause, solution, prevention, occurrence_count, tags.</reference>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="usage-rules">
      <p>Rules for template usage: do not add sections, run Confidence Check at four gates, token estimation guide, agent self-logging pattern.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Do not add sections to templates beyond what is defined. Template constraints are intentional — they keep output structure consistent for downstream agents to parse.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents adding custom sections make output unparseable for executor agents expecting standard fields. Approve custom sections only through an explicit decision recorded in the Constitution.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always use the template as-is for the first version; resist the urge to add custom sections until the standard ones are proven insufficient.</statement>
        <rationale>Custom sections multiply inconsistency. Wait until three instances of the same missing field before proposing a Constitution change.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>The Confidence Check template should be run at four explicit gates: Pre-Spec, Pre-Design, Pre-Task, Pre-Implementation — skip none.</statement>
        <rationale>Each gate catches different classes of problems early. Pre-Spec gates catch vague requirements. Pre-Design gates catch missed architecture choices. Pre-Task gates catch over-scoped tasks. Pre-Implementation gates catch incomplete dependency information.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Token Estimation Guide values are approximate and assume average file sizes; generated code (e.g., GraphQL schema, Prisma client) can be 5–10x larger.</statement>
        <rationale>Baseline estimates from the guide are known-underestimates for generated or highly repetitive code. Add multipliers for large codegen or schema tasks.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>The Constitution template is underspecified for multi-repo projects — add a "Repos" table listing each repo, its language, and its deploy target.</statement>
        <rationale>Multi-repo projects have topology constraints that single-repo projects don't. Make dependency/ownership explicit upfront.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pattern Record and Mistake Record JSON templates should be stored in .aidocs/memory/ and indexed — agents that cannot find prior patterns repeat mistakes.</statement>
        <rationale>Unindexed memory is not searchable. Add a PATTERN-INDEX.md or ERROR-INDEX.md that summarizes all recorded patterns and errors per month or per project phase.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-workflows">
      <p>How agents use templates as output schemas and for self-logging.</p>
      <p>Agents use templates as output schemas: provide the template as part of the system prompt and instruct the agent to fill each section. This constrains output structure and prevents agents from inventing non-standard sections. For implementation plans, the wave/checkpoint structure in the template ensures the executor agent can process tasks in dependency order without re-reading the entire plan.</p>
      <p>The Pattern Record and Mistake Record templates are designed for agent self-logging: after each task, the executor agent appends a record to patterns.md or mistakes.md in .aidocs/memory/.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <p>Known constraints and gotchas when using templates at scale.</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents filling templates often leave {placeholder} text in non-obvious fields (e.g., "Project: {project-name}").</description>
        <reason>Run grep for '{' in generated docs before committing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>The Implementation Plan template's Dependency Graph section is frequently left as freetext; agents do not auto-detect circular deps.</description>
        <reason>Validate the dependency graph manually before approving the plan.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Execution reports written by faion-sdd-executor-agent may not match the TASK_*.md template structure if the task file deviates.</description>
        <reason>Strict template adherence in task files prevents this; review all created tasks against the template.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Est. tokens" fields in implementation plan tables are often optimistic by 30–50% in practice.</description>
        <reason>Add a review pass that stress-tests estimates against actual file sizes before committing to the plan.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>The Roadmap template uses "Now / Next / Later" quarters; for long-lived projects this drifts.</description>
        <reason>Prefer milestone labels over calendar quarters for long-lived projects.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/constitution.md" purpose="Project Constitution skeleton (vision, tech stack, patterns, standards, quality gates)."/>
      <template path="templates/implementation-plan.md" purpose="Implementation Plan skeleton (overview, task table, dependency graph, waves, quality gates)."/>
      <template path="templates/backlog-item.md" purpose="Backlog item skeleton (priority, RICE score, problem, AC, dependencies)."/>
      <template path="templates/confidence-check.md" purpose="Confidence Check skeleton (score table, verdict, gaps)."/>
      <template path="templates/pattern-record.json" purpose="JSON schema for agent-logged successful patterns."/>
      <template path="templates/mistake-record.json" purpose="JSON schema for agent-logged errors and solutions."/>
      <template path="templates/new-feature.sh" purpose="Shell script to scaffold a new feature directory with stub spec and impl plan."/>
      <template path="templates/roadmap.md" purpose="Roadmap skeleton (Now/Next/Later sections with milestones and statuses)."/>
    </templates>

